图书 Ngram 查看器

发行说明

Release Notes


2024年7月

July 2024

有新数据集可用

New dataset available

新增了 Ngram Viewer 数据集。新数据集发布时，会包含最新的单词和短语，因此某些 Ngram 的图表可能会有所变化。由于 OCR 和语言检测功能的改进，以及书籍添加到我们的语料库中，图表也会持续更新。

A new Ngram Viewer dataset has been added. When new datasets are released, they contain up-to-date words and phrases, so charts for some ngrams may change. Charts also continue to change due to improvements in OCR and language detection, and as books are added to our corpus.

之前的数据集（2009、2012、2019）已从语料库下拉菜单中移除，但仍可使用搜索运算符
（:eng_2019、:fre_2012等）进行访问。您可以继续使用指向旧数据集的 URL。

Previous datasets (2009, 2012, 2019) have been removed from the corpus pulldown, but are still available and can be accessed using search operators
(:eng_2019, :fre_2012, etc.). You can continue to use URLs that point to older datasets.

Ngram Viewer 搜索支持更多词汇

Support for more words in Ngram Viewer search

现在，Ngram Viewer 搜索查询最多可包含 7 个单词（之前限制为 5 个）。词性支持仍然限制为每次查询 1-5 个词元。

You can now include up to 7 words in your Ngram Viewer search query (previously limited to 5). Part-of-speech support is still limited to 1-5 tokens per query.


Ngram 查看器有什么作用？

What does the Ngram Viewer do?

当你在 Google 图书 Ngram 查看器中输入短语时，它会显示一个图表，显示这些短语在所选年份的图书语料库（例如“英式英语”、“英国小说”、“法语”）中的出现情况。我们来看一个示例图表：

When you enter phrases into the Google Books Ngram Viewer, it displays a graph showing how those phrases have occurred in a corpus of books (e.g., "British English", "English Fiction", "French") over the selected years. Let's look at a sample graph:


这幅图展示了 1960 年至 2015 年三个 ngram 的趋势：“nursery school”（ 二元词组，或称bigram）、“kindergarten”（一元词组，或 称 unigram）和“child care”（另一个二元词组）。y 轴显示的是：在我们样本美国出版的英文书籍的所有二元词组中，有多少百分比是“nursery school”或“c​​hild care”？在所有 unigram 中，有多少百分比是“kindergarten”？从图中可以看出，“child care”这一短语的使用率在 20 世纪 60 年代末开始上升，在 1970 年左右超过了“nursery school”，然后在 1973 年左右超过了“kindergarten”。它在 1990 年后不久达到顶峰，此后一直在稳步下降。

This shows trends in three ngrams from 1960 to 2015: "nursery school" (a 2-gram or bigram), "kindergarten" (a 1-gram or unigram), and "child care" (another bigram). What the y-axis shows is this: of all the bigrams contained in our sample of books written in English and published in the United States, what percentage of them are "nursery school" or "child care"? Of all the unigrams, what percentage of them are "kindergarten"? Here, you can see that use of the phrase "child care" started to rise in the late 1960s, overtaking "nursery school" around 1970 and then "kindergarten" around 1973. It peaked shortly after 1990 and has been falling steadily since.

（有趣的是，当语料库切换到英式英语时，结果明显不同。）

(Interestingly, the results are noticeably different when the corpus is switched to British English.)

您可以将鼠标悬停在某个 ngram 的线图上，它会高亮显示该 ngram。左键单击线图，即可聚焦于某个特定的 ngram，图表中的其他 ngram（如有）会变灰。随后，左键单击图表中的其他 ngram，即可聚焦于多个 ngram。双击图表的任意区域，即可恢复查询中的所有 ngram。

You can hover over the line plot for an ngram, which highlights it. With a left-click on a line plot, you can focus on a particular ngram, greying out the other ngrams in the chart, if any. On subsequent left clicks on other line plots in the chart, multiple ngrams can be focused on. You can double click on any area of the chart to reinstate all the ngrams in the query.

您还可以在查询中指定通配符、搜索词形变化、执行不区分大小写的搜索、查找特定的词性，或者对 ngram 进行加、减、除运算。更多详情请参阅 高级用法

You can also specify wildcards in queries, search for inflections, perform case insensitive search, look for particular parts of speech, or add, subtract, and divide ngrams. More on those under Advanced Usage



高级用法

Advanced Usage

Ngram Viewer 的一些功能可能会吸引那些想要更深入地了解短语用法的用户：通配符搜索、 词形变化搜索、不区分大小写搜索、 词性标签和ngram 组合。

A few features of the Ngram Viewer may appeal to users who want to dig a little deeper into phrase usage: wildcard search, inflection search, case insensitive search, part-of-speech tags and ngram compositions.

通配符搜索

Wildcard search

当你用 代替*某个单词时，Ngram Viewer 会显示前十个替代词。例如，要查找“University of”之后最流行的单词，请搜索“ University of * ” 。

When you put a * in place of a word, the Ngram Viewer will display the top ten substitutions. For instance, to find the most popular words following "University of", search for " University of *."

您可以右键单击任意替换 ngram，将其全部折叠到原始通配符查询中，结果为替换项按年份的总和。随后右键单击会将通配符查询扩展回所有替换项。请注意，Ngram 查看器每个 ngram 仅支持一个 *。

You can right click on any of the replacement ngrams to collapse them all into the original wildcard query, with the result being the yearwise sum of the replacements. A subsequent right click expands the wildcard query back to all the replacements. Note that the Ngram Viewer only supports one * per ngram.

请注意，前十个替换词是针对指定时间范围计算的。因此，您可能会根据不同的年份范围获得不同的替换词。我们从前十个列表中筛选出了标点符号，但对于经常用于句子开头或结尾的单词，您可能会看到句子边界符号（_START_或_END_）作为替换词之一。

Note that the top ten replacements are computed for the specified time range. You might therefore get different replacements for different year ranges. We've filtered punctuation symbols from the top ten list, but for words that often start or end sentences, you might see one of the sentence boundary symbols (_START_ or _END_) as one of the replacements.


词形变化搜索

Inflection search

词形变化是指对单词进行修饰，以表示各种语法类别，例如体、格、性、语气、数、人称、时态和语态。您可以通过在 ngram 后附加 _INF 来搜索它们。例如，搜索“ book _INFa hotel ”将显示“book”、“booked”、“books”和“booking”的结果：

An inflection is the modification of a word to represent various grammatical categories such as aspect, case, gender, mood, number, person, tense and voice. You can search for them by appending _INF to an ngram. For instance, searching " book_INF a hotel" will display results for "book", "booked", "books", and "booking":

右键单击任意词形变化，即可将所有词形变化折叠成总和。请注意，Ngram Viewer_INF每次查询仅支持一个关键词。

Right clicking any inflection collapses all forms into their sum. Note that the Ngram Viewer only supports one _INF keyword per query.

警告：您不能随意混合使用通配符搜索、词形变化搜索和不区分大小写的搜索来搜索某个特定的 ngram。但是，您可以使用以下任一功能搜索查询中的不同 ngram：“book _INFa hotel, book * hotel” 可以，但“book _INF* hotel” 不行。

Warning: You can't freely mix wildcard searches, inflections and case-insensitive searches for one particular ngram. However, you can search with either of these features for separate ngrams in a query: "book_INF a hotel, book * hotel" is fine, but "book_INF * hotel" is not.


不区分大小写的搜索

Case insensitive search

默认情况下，Ngram Viewer 执行区分大小写的搜索：大小写很重要。您可以通过选中查询框右侧的“不区分大小写”复选框来执行不区分大小写的搜索。Ngram Viewer 将显示输入查询的年度最常见不区分大小写变体的总数。以下是两个不区分大小写的 ngram： “Fitzgerald”和“Dupont”：

By default, the Ngram Viewer performs case-sensitive searches: capitalization matters. You can perform a case-insensitive search by selecting the "case-insensitive" checkbox to the right of the query box. The Ngram Viewer will then display the yearwise sum of the most common case-insensitive variants of the input query. Here are two case-insensitive ngrams, "Fitzgerald" and "Dupont":

右键单击任意年份总计，即可展开为最常见的不区分大小写的变体。例如，右键单击“杜邦（全部）”，会显示以下四个变体：“杜邦”、“杜邦”、“杜邦”和“杜邦”。

Right clicking any yearwise sum results in an expansion into the most common case-insensitive variants. For example, a right click on "Dupont (All)" results in the following four variants: "DuPont", "Dupont", "duPont" and "DUPONT".


词性标签

Part-of-speech Tags

以单词tackle为例，它可以是动词（“解决问题”），也可以是名词（“钓具”）。您可以通过在后面添加_VERB或来区分这些不同的形式_NOUN，例如：“ tackle _VERB, tackle_NOUN ”

Consider the word tackle, which can be a verb ("tackle the problem") or a noun ("fishing tackle"). You can distinguish between these different forms by appending _VERB or _NOUN, example: " tackle_VERB, tackle_NOUN"

完整标签列表如下：

The full list of tags is as follows:

_NOUN_ 名词 这些标签可以独立存在（_PRON_）
，也可以附加到单词（ she_ PRON）
_PROPN_ 专有名词
_VERB_ 动词
_ADJ_ 形容词
_ADV_ 副词
_PRON_ 代词
_DET_ 限定词或冠词
_ADP_ 介词：介词或后置词
_NUM_ 数字
_CONJ_ 连词
_PRT_ 粒子
_ROOT_ 解析树的根 这些标签必须独立（例如_START_）
_START_ 句子的开头
_END_ 句子结尾

由于词性标签不需要附加到特定的单词，因此您可以使用标签DET来搜索读一本书、 读这本书、读那本书、读这本书等等，如下所示，“ 读书_DET_”：

Since the part-of-speech tags needn't attach to particular words, you can use the DET tag to search for read a book, read the book, read that book, read this book, and so on as follows, " read _DET_ book":

如果你想知道这种情况下最常见的限定词是什么，你可以结合通配符和词性标签来 阅读书籍： *_DET

If you wanted to know what the most common determiners in this context are, you could combine wildcards and part-of-speech tags to read *_DET book:

要获取语料库中 后面跟着 a 的单词book 的所有不同词形变化，您可以发出查询book： NOUN _INF _NOUN_

To get all the different inflections of the word book which have been followed by a NOUN in the corpus you can issue the query book_INF _NOUN_:

可以使用通配符功能检索单词最常用的词性标记。考虑查询 cooks_*：

Most frequent part-of-speech tags for a word can be retrieved with the wildcard functionality. Consider the query cooks_*:

词形变化关键词也可以与词性标签结合使用。例如，考虑下面的查询 cook , cook ，它分离了“cook”动词义的词形变化： _INF_VERB_INF

The inflection keyword can also be combined with part-of-speech tags. For example, consider the query cook_INF, cook_VERB_INF below, that separates out the inflections of the verbal sense of "cook":

_START_Ngram 查看器标记句子边界，允许您使用和 标签 识别句子开头和结尾的 ngram _END_，例如：“杜鲁门总统、林肯总统、哈丁总统” _START__START__START_

The Ngram Viewer tags sentence boundaries, allowing you to identify ngrams at starts and ends of sentences with the _START_ and _END_ tags, example: " _START_ President Truman,_START_ President Lincoln,_START_ President Harding"

有时，用依赖关系而非模式来思考单词会更有帮助。假设你想知道tasty修饰 dessert 的频率。也就是说，你想统计 tasty frost dessert、crunchy, tasty dessert、 tasty yet expensive dessert的提及次数，以及所有其他将tasty一词应用于dessert的情况。为此，Ngram Viewer 提供了与=>运算符 dessert =>tasty 的依赖关系：

Sometimes it helps to think about words in terms of dependencies rather than patterns. Let's say you want to know how often tasty modifies dessert. That is, you want to tally mentions of tasty frozen dessert, crunchy, tasty dessert, tasty yet expensive dessert, and all the other instances in which the word tasty is applied to dessert. For that, the Ngram Viewer provides dependency relations with the => operator dessert=>tasty:

每个解析后的句子都有一个_ROOT_。与其他标签不同， _ROOT_并不代表句子中的特定单词或位置。它是通过分析语法构建的解析树的根；你可以将其视为句子主要动词所修饰内容的占位符。因此，以下是如何识别will是句子主要动词“ will ”的频率： _ROOT_=>

Every parsed sentence has a _ROOT_. Unlike other tags, _ROOT_ doesn't stand for a particular word or position in the sentence. It's the root of the parse tree constructed by analyzing the syntax; you can think of it as a placeholder for what the main verb of the sentence is modifying. So here's how to identify how often will was the main verb of a sentence, " _ROOT_=>will":

上图包含句子Larry will decision.但不包括Larry said that he will decision，因为will不是该句子的主要动词。

The above graph would include the sentence Larry will decide. but not Larry said that he will decide, since will isn't the main verb of that sentence.

依赖项可以使用通配符组合。例如，请考虑下面的查询 drink=>* ： _NOUN

Dependencies can be combined with wildcards. For example, consider the query drink=>*_NOUN below:

“纯”词性标记可以与 1-、2-、3-、4- 和 5-gram 中的常规单词自由混合（例如，the _ADJ_ toast或 _DET_ _ADJ_ toast）。“明亮的彩虹” _DET__ADJ

"Pure" part-of-speech tags can be mixed freely with regular words in 1-, 2-, 3-, 4-, and 5-grams (e.g., the _ADJ_ toast or _DET_ _ADJ_ toast). " _DET_ bright_ADJ rainbow"


Ngram 组合

Ngram Compositions

Ngram Viewer 提供了五个可用于组合 ngram 的运算 符 ：+、、、和 -。/*:

The Ngram Viewer provides five operators that you can use to combine ngrams: +, -, /, *, and :.

+ 对两侧的表达式求和，让您将多个 ngram 时间序列合并为一个。
- 将左侧表达式减去右侧表达式，从而可以衡量一个 ngram 相对于另一个 ngram 的比率。由于用户经常搜索带连字符的短语，因此请在符号两侧添加空格-。
/ 将左边的表达式除以右边的表达式，这对于隔离一个 ngram 相对于另一个 ngram 的行为很有用。
* 将左侧的表达式乘以右侧的数字，以便更轻松地比较频率差异很大的 ngram。（请务必将整个 ngram 括在括号中，以免 * 被解释为通配符。）
: 将左侧的 ngram 应用于右侧的语料库，允许您比较不同语料库中的 ngram。

Ngram Viewer 会尝试猜测是否应用这些行为。您可以使用括号强制启用它们，使用方括号强制禁用它们。例如：and/or会将and除以or；要衡量短语and/or 的使用情况，请使用[and/or]。andwell-meaning会搜索短语 well-meaning；如果您想从 well 中减去 meaning ，请使用 (well - meaning)。

The Ngram Viewer will try to guess whether to apply these behaviors. You can use parentheses to force them on, and square brackets to force them off. Example: and/or will divide and by or; to measure the usage of the phrase and/or, use [and/or]. And well-meaning will search for the phrase well-meaning; if you want to subtract meaning from well, use (well - meaning).

为了演示该运算符，您可以按照以下方式找到game、sport和play、 game 、 sport 、 play+的总和 ( game + sport + play )：

To demonstrate the + operator, here's how you might find the sum of game, sport, and play, game, sport ,play, (game + sport + play):

在确定人们多年来是否写了更多关于选择的文章时，你可以比较choice、selection、option和 alternative，并指定名词形式以避免形容词形式（例如choice delicacy、alternative music），例如“ (choice _NOUN+ selection _NOUN+ option _NOUN + alternative _NOUN) ”：

When determining whether people wrote more about choices over the years, you could compare choice, selection, option, and alternative, specifying the noun forms to avoid the adjective forms (e.g., choice delicacy, alternative music), example " (choice_NOUN + selection_NOUN + option_NOUN + alternative_NOUN)":

Ngram 减法让你可以轻松地将一组 ngram 与另一组 ngram 进行比较，“ ((Bigfoot + Sasquatch) - (Loch Ness monster + Nessie)) ”：

Ngram subtraction gives you an easy way to compare one set of ngrams to another, " ((Bigfoot + Sasquatch) - (Loch Ness monster + Nessie))":

为了展示单词applesauce是如何以牺牲applesauce为代价而发展起来的 +，你 可以这样组合“ (applesauce / (apple sauce + applesauce)) ”： /

Here's how you might combine + and / to show how the word applesauce has blossomed at the expense of apple sauce, " (applesauce / (apple sauce + applesauce))":

*当你想要比较频率差异很大的 ngram 时， 此运算符很有用，例如小提琴和更深奥的特雷 门琴，“ (特雷门琴 * 1000),小提琴”：

The * operator is useful when you want to compare ngrams of widely varying frequencies, like violin and the more esoteric theremin, " (theremin * 1000),violin":

选择运算符:corpus可以让你比较不同语言的 ngram，例如美式英语与英式英语（或小说），或者比较 2009 年、2012 年、2019 年和当前版本的图书扫描结果。以下是英语的chat与法语的同一 unigram，即“ chat:fre, chat:eng ”的比较：

The :corpus selection operator lets you compare ngrams in different languages, or American versus British English (or fiction), or between the 2009, 2012, 2019, and the current versions of our book scans. Here's chat in English versus the same unigram in French, " chat:fre, chat:eng":

当我们在 2009 年生成原始 Ngram Viewer 语料库时，我们的 OCR 效果不如现在。这在 19 世纪之前的英语中尤为明显，当时的长音中间音 s (ſ) 通常被理解为 f，所以best通常被读作beft。以下是我们自那时以来所取得的改进的证据，我们使用语料库运算符比较了 2009、2012、2019 和当前版本：“ beft:eng,beft:eng_2019,beft:eng_2012,beft:eng_2009 ”：

When we generated the original Ngram Viewer corpora in 2009, our OCR wasn't as good as it is today. This was especially obvious in pre-19th century English, where the elongated medial-s (ſ) was often interpreted as an f, so best was often read as beft. Here's evidence of the improvements we've made since then, using the corpus operator to compare the 2009, 2012, 2019 and Current versions, " beft:eng,beft:eng_2019,beft:eng_2012,beft:eng_2009":

通过将小说与所有英语进行比较，我们可以看到，与小说中的用法 相比， wizard在一般英语中的用法最近有所增加，“ (wizard:eng / wizard:eng_fiction) ”：

By comparing fiction against all of English, we can see that uses of wizard in general English have been gaining recently compared to uses in fiction, " (wizard:eng / wizard:eng_fiction)":

语料库

Corpora

以下是可使用 Google Books Ngram Viewer 搜索的语料库的描述。所有语料库均于 2009 年 7 月、2012 年 7 月和 2020 年 2 月生成；随着图书扫描的继续，我们将更新这些语料库，更新后的版本将具有独特的永久标识符。OCR 质量较低的图书和期刊被排除在外。

Below are descriptions of the corpora that can be searched with the Google Books Ngram Viewer. All corpora were generated in July 2009, July 2012, and February 2020; we will update these corpora as our book scanning continues, and the updated versions will have distinct persistent identifiers. Books with low OCR quality and serials were excluded.

西班牙语 温泉 主要以西班牙语为主的书籍。
西班牙语 2019 spa_2019 googlebooks-spa-20200217
2012年西班牙 spa_2012 googlebooks-spa-all-20120701
2009年西班牙 spa_2009 googlebooks-spa-all-20090715
俄语 罗斯 书籍主要以俄语为主。
俄罗斯2019 rus_2019 googlebooks-rus-20200217
2012年俄罗斯 rus_2012 googlebooks-rus-all-20120701
俄罗斯 2009 rus_2009 googlebooks-rus-all-20090715
意大利语 伊塔 主要以意大利语为主的书籍。
意大利语 2019 ita_2019 googlebooks-ita-20200217
意大利 2012 ita_2012 googlebooks-ita-all-20120701

与 2009 年版本相比，2012 年、2019 年和季度发布的版本包含更多图书，改进了 OCR 功能，并改进了图书馆和出版商的元数据。2012 年和 2019 年版本不会形成跨句子边界的 ngram，但会形成跨页面边界的 ngram，这与 2009 年版本不同。

Compared to the 2009 versions, the 2012, 2019, and quarterly released versions have more books, improved OCR, improved library and publisher metadata. The 2012 and 2019 versions also don't form ngrams that cross sentence boundaries, and do form ngrams across page boundaries, unlike the 2009 versions.

在最新的语料库中，分词方法也得到了改进，使用了一套人工设计的规则（中文除外，中文使用统计系统进行分词）。在2009年的语料库中，分词方法仅仅基于空格。

With the most recent corpora, the tokenization has improved as well, using a set of manually devised rules (except for Chinese, where a statistical system is used for segmentation). In the 2009 corpora, tokenization was based simply on whitespace.

在 Google 图书内搜索

Searching inside Google Books

图表下方显示了与您的查询词相关的“有趣”年份范围。点击这些年份范围即可将您的查询直接提交至 Google 图书。请注意，Ngram 查看器区分大小写，但 Google 图书搜索结果 不区分大小写。

Below the graph, we show "interesting" year ranges for your query terms. Clicking on those will submit your query directly to Google Books. Note that the Ngram Viewer is case-sensitive, but Google Books search results are not.

这些搜索会返回你所选语料库语言的短语，但结果来自完整的 Google 图书语料库。因此，如果你使用 Ngram Viewer 在法语语料库中搜索法语短语，然后点击进入 Google 图书，搜索结果将是相同的法语短语——而这个短语可能出现在以其他语言为主的书籍中。

Those searches will yield phrases in the language of whichever corpus you selected, but the results are returned from the full Google Books corpus. So if you use the Ngram Viewer to search for a French phrase in the French corpus and then click through to Google Books, that search will be for the same French phrase -- which might occur in a book predominantly in another language.

常见问题解答

FAQs


为什么我没有看到我期望的结果？

Why am I not seeing the results I expect?

或许是出于以下原因之一：

  • Ngram 查看器区分大小写。请尝试将查询词首字母大写，或勾选搜索框右侧的“不区分大小写”复选框。
  • 您正在搜索一个意想不到的语料库。例如， 《弗兰肯斯坦》没有出现在俄语书籍中，所以如果您在俄语语料库中搜索，您会看到一条直线。您可以通过搜索框下方的下拉菜单或语料库选择运算符（例如 ）来选择语料库Frankenstein:eng_2019。
  • 您的短语中包含逗号、加号、连字符、星号、冒号或斜杠。这些符号对 Ngram 查看器有特殊含义；请参阅 高级用法。请尝试将短语括在方括号中（尽管逗号无效）。

Perhaps for one of these reasons:

  • The Ngram Viewer is case-sensitive. Try capitalizing your query or check the "case-insensitive" box to the right of the search box.
  • You're searching in an unexpected corpus. For instance, Frankenstein doesn't appear in Russian books, so if you search in the Russian corpus you'll see a flatline. You can choose the corpus via the dropdown menu below the search box, or through the corpus selection operator, e.g., Frankenstein:eng_2019.
  • Your phrase has a comma, plus sign, hyphen, asterisk, colon, or forward slash in it. Those have special meanings to the Ngram Viewer; see Advanced Usage. Try enclosing the phrase in square brackets (although this won't help with commas).

Ngram Viewer 如何处理标点符号？

How does the Ngram Viewer handle punctuation?

我们应用了一组特定于特定语言的标记规则。在英语中，缩写变成两个单词（they're 成为二元语法they 're、we'll成为 we 'll等等）。所有格's也被拆分开来，但R'n'B仍然是一个标记。否定（n't）被规范化，因此don't成为 do not。在俄语中，变音符号ё被规范化为e，等等。相同的规则用于解析用户输入的 ngram 和从语料库中提取的 ngram，这意味着如果您正在搜索don't，请不要对 Ngram Viewer 将其重写为的事实感到震惊do not；它准确地描述了语料库中don't和 的用法do not。但是，这意味着无法明确搜索特定形式can't（或 cannot）：您会同时 得到can't和 can not和。cannot

We apply a set of tokenization rules specific to the particular language. In English, contractions become two words (they're becomes the bigram they 're, we'll becomes we 'll, and so on). The possessive 's is also split off, but R'n'B remains one token. Negations (n't) are normalized so that don't becomes do not. In Russian, the diacritic ё is normalized to e, and so on. The same rules are applied to parse both the ngrams typed by users and the ngrams extracted from the corpora, which means that if you're searching for don't, don't be alarmed by the fact that the Ngram Viewer rewrites it to do not; it is accurately depicting usages of both don't and do not in the corpus. However, this means there is no way to search explicitly for the specific forms can't (or cannot): you get can't and can not and cannot all at once.

我怎样才能看到上下文中的示例用法？

How can I see sample usages in context?

在 Ngram Viewer 图表下方，我们提供了一个预先定义的 Google 图书搜索表格，每个搜索都缩小到某个年份范围。我们根据兴趣度来选择范围：如果某个 ngram 在某一年份出现了巨大的峰值，那么该年份就会单独显示为搜索词，其他搜索词则涵盖更长的时间段。

与 Ngram Viewer 语料库不同，Google Books 语料库没有词性标记。例如，在 Google Books 中无法搜索 cheer的动词形式。因此，任何带有词性标记（例如cheer_VERB）的 ngram 都会被排除在 Google Books 搜索表之外。

Ngram Viewer 包含 2009、2012、2019 年以及每季度发布的语料库，但 Google 图书并非如此。当您在 Google 图书中搜索时，您搜索的是所有当前可用的图书，因此您在 Google 图书中看到的内容与您在 Ngram Viewer 图表中预期看到的内容之间可能会存在一些差异。

Below the Ngram Viewer chart, we provide a table of predefined Google Books searches, each narrowed to a range of years. We choose the ranges according to interestingness: if an ngram has a huge peak in a particular year, that will appear by itself as a search, with other searches covering longer durations.

Unlike the Ngram Viewer corpus, the Google Books corpus isn't part-of-speech tagged. One can't search for, say, the verb form of cheer in Google Books. So any ngrams with part-of-speech tags (e.g., cheer_VERB) are excluded from the table of Google Books searches.

The Ngram Viewer has 2009, 2012, 2019 and a quarterly released corpora, but Google Books doesn't work that way. When you're searching in Google Books, you're searching all the currently available books, so there may be some differences between what you see in Google Books and what you would expect to see given the Ngram Viewer chart.

为什么我在早年看到更多的峰值和平台期？

Why do I see more spikes and plateaus in early years?

在16和17世纪，出版是一件相对罕见的事情。（19世纪之前，英文书籍出版量仅有 约50万本。）因此，如果某个短语在某一年出现在一本书中，但在前后几年都没有出现，那么它产生的峰值会比之后几年更高。

平台期通常只是平滑的尖峰。将平滑度改为 0。

Publishing was a relatively rare event in the 16th and 17th centuries. (There are only about 500,000 books published in English before the 19th century.) So if a phrase occurs in one book in one year but not in the preceding or following years, that creates a taller spike than it would in later years.

Plateaus are usually simply smoothed spikes. Change the smoothing to 0.

“平滑”是什么意思？

What does "smoothing" mean?

通常，当数据以移动平均值的形式呈现时，趋势会更加明显。平滑度为 1 表示 1950 年的数据将是 1950 年原始计数的平均值，加上两边各 1 个值：（“1949 年计数” + “1950 年计数” + “1951 年计数”），再除以 3。因此，平滑度为 10 表示将对 21 个值进行平均：两边各 10 个值，加上中间的目标值。

在图表的左右边缘，取平均值的数值较少。如果平滑度为 3，则最左边的值（假设是 1950 年）的计算公式为（“1950 年的计数” + “1951 年的计数” + “1952 年的计数” + “1953 年的计数”）除以 4。

平滑度为 0 表示根本没有平滑：只是原始数据。

Often trends become more apparent when data is viewed as a moving average. A smoothing of 1 means that the data shown for 1950 will be an average of the raw count for 1950 plus 1 value on either side: ("count for 1949" + "count for 1950" + "count for 1951"), divided by 3. So a smoothing of 10 means that 21 values will be averaged: 10 on either side, plus the target value in the center of them.

At the left and right edges of the graph, fewer values are averaged. With a smoothing of 3, the leftmost value (pretend it's the year 1950) will be calculated as ("count for 1950" + "count for 1951" + "count for 1952" + "count for 1953"), divided by 4.

A smoothing of 0 means no smoothing at all: just raw data.

近年来出版的书籍数量大幅增加。这是否会扭曲结果？

Many more books are published in modern years. Doesn't this skew the results?

如果我们不根据每年出版的书籍数量进行标准化，情况就会如此。

It would if we didn't normalize by the number of books published in each year.

当我知道我的查询中的短语至少出现在一本书中时，为什么会显示 0% 的直线？

Why are you showing a 0% flatline when I know the phrase in my query occurred in at least one book?

在高负载下，Ngram Viewer 有时会返回一条直线；请重新加载以确认该短语确实没有匹配项。此外，我们只考虑至少在 40 本书中出现的 ngram。否则，数据集会膨胀，我们将无法提供 所有匹配项。

Under heavy load, the Ngram Viewer will sometimes return a flatline; reload to confirm that there are actually no hits for the phrase. Also, we only consider ngrams that occur in at least 40 books. Otherwise the dataset would balloon in size and we wouldn't be able to offer them all.

词性标注的准确度如何？

How accurate is the part-of-speech tagging?

词性标记和依存关系是自动预测的。评估这些预测的准确性很困难，但对于现代英语，我们预计词性标记的准确率约为 95%，依存关系的准确率约为 85%。对于较旧的英语文本和其他语言，准确率较低，但词性标记的准确率可能超过 90%，依存关系的准确率可能超过 75%。这意味着存在大量错误，在得出结论时应予以考虑。

词性标记基于小型训练集（仅包含一百万个英语单词）构建。这有时会低估一些不常见的用法，例如将green、dog或book用作动词，或将 ask用作名词。

关于中文的补充说明：20世纪之前，所有书面交流都使用文言文。文言文基于古汉语的语法和词汇，因此句法注释的错误率会高于正确率。

另请注意，2009 年语料库尚未标注词性。

The part-of-speech tags and dependency relations are predicted automatically. Assessing the accuracy of these predictions is difficult, but for modern English we expect the accuracy of the part-of-speech tags to be around 95% and the accuracy of dependency relations around 85%. On older English text and for other languages the accuracies are lower, but likely above 90% for part-of-speech tags and above 75% for dependencies. This implies a significant number of errors, which should be taken into account when drawing conclusions.

The part-of-speech tags are constructed from a small training set (a mere million words for English). This will sometimes underrepresent uncommon usages, such as green or dog or book as verbs, or ask as a noun.

An additional note on Chinese: Before the 20th century, classical Chinese was traditionally used for all written communication. Classical Chinese is based on the grammar and vocabulary of ancient Chinese, and the syntactic annotations will therefore be wrong more often than they're right.

Also, note that the 2009 corpora have not been part-of-speech tagged.

我正在根据您的研究成果撰写一篇论文。我该如何引用您的研究成果？

I'm writing a paper based on your results. How can I cite your work?

如果您要将此数据用于学术出版物，请引用原始论文：

Jean-Baptiste Michel*、Yuan Kui Shen、Aviva Presser Aiden、Adrian Veres、Matthew K. Gray、William Brockman、Google 图书团队、Joseph P. Pickett、Dale Hoiberg、Dan Clancy、Peter Norvig、Jon Orwant、Steven Pinker、Martin A. Nowak 和 Erez Lieberman Aiden*。《 基于数百万本数字化图书的文化定量分析》。《科学》（在线预印版发表日期：2010年12月16日）

我们还有一篇关于词性标注的论文：

Yuri Lin, Jean-Baptiste Michel, Erez Lieberman Aiden, Jon Orwant, William Brockman, Slav Petrov. Google Books Ngram 语料库的句法标注. 计算语言学协会第50届年会论文集 第二卷：演示论文 (ACL '12) (2012)

If you're going to use this data for an academic publication, please cite the original paper:

Jean-Baptiste Michel*, Yuan Kui Shen, Aviva Presser Aiden, Adrian Veres, Matthew K. Gray, William Brockman, The Google Books Team, Joseph P. Pickett, Dale Hoiberg, Dan Clancy, Peter Norvig, Jon Orwant, Steven Pinker, Martin A. Nowak, and Erez Lieberman Aiden*. Quantitative Analysis of Culture Using Millions of Digitized Books. Science (Published online ahead of print: 12/16/2010)

We also have a paper on our part-of-speech tagging:

Yuri Lin, Jean-Baptiste Michel, Erez Lieberman Aiden, Jon Orwant, William Brockman, Slav Petrov. Syntactic Annotations for the Google Books Ngram Corpus. Proceedings of the 50th Annual Meeting of the Association for Computational Linguistics Volume 2: Demo Papers (ACL '12) (2012)

我可以下载您的数据来运行我自己的实验吗？

Can I download your data to run my own experiments?

是的！ngram 数据可 在此处下载。为了方便管理文件大小，我们按首字母对数据进行了分组，并将不同大小的 ngram 分组到单独的文件中。每个文件中的 ngram 不按字母顺序排序。

为了生成机器可读的文件名，我们对使用非罗马字母（中文、希伯来语、俄语）的 ngram 进行了音译，并使用音译后的 ngram 的首字母来确定文件名。 对于德语中的ä等字符，我们也采取了同样的方法。请注意，音译仅用于确定文件名；实际的 ngram 是使用特定语言字母表以 UTF-8 编码的。

Yes! The ngram data is available for download here. To make the file sizes manageable, we've grouped them by their starting letter and then grouped the different ngram sizes in separate files. The ngrams within each file are not alphabetically sorted.

To generate machine-readable filenames, we transliterated the ngrams for languages that use non-roman scripts (Chinese, Hebrew, Russian) and used the starting letter of the transliterated ngram to determine the filename. The same approach was taken for characters such as ä in German. Note that the transliteration was used only to determine the filename; the actual ngrams are encoded in UTF-8 using the language-specific alphabet.

我想在我的书籍/杂志/博客/演示文稿中发布 Ngram 图表。你们的许可条款是什么？

I'd like to publish an Ngram graph in my book/magazine/blog/presentation. What are your licensing terms?

Ngram Viewer 图表和数据可自由用于任何目的，但如能注明来源为 Google Books Ngram Viewer 并附上https://books.google.com/ngrams 的链接 ，我们将不胜感激。

Ngram Viewer graphs and data may be freely used for any purpose, although acknowledgement of Google Books Ngram Viewer as the source, and inclusion of a link to https://books.google.com/ngrams, would be appreciated.
